recordings.loc: São Desidério, Bahia
recordings.rmk:
This is a first record of the Veery Catharus fuscescens (Stephens, 1817) in the state of Bahia. 
On the morning (5:25 am) of December 11, 2019, in a fragment of Seasonal Tropical Dry Forest in São Desidério, an young individual of C. fuscescens was captured in a mist net. 
After the capture, the animal vocalize its distress call inside the containment bag.
The manuscript with all information is in the process of being submitted to the specialized journal.
The distress call  can be noticed at 16 and 45 seconds of recording.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Cut from a longer recording (~3.5min) in which Blue Jays are mobbing something in the forest. At least 3 Veeries can be heard calling from the forest understory in response to the mobbing. The individual in this recording was the closest to the forest edge and was seen. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Nockamixon SP, Bucks County, Pennsylvania
New Jersey (near  Gillette), Morris County, New Jersey
New York (near  Millbrook), Dutchess County, New York
recordings.rmk:
This original record was made by Wieteke A. Holthuijzen as part of a long-term study initiated and supervised by Dr. Kenneth A. Schmidt (Assistant Professor, Behavioral Ecology of Birds and Mammals, Texas Tech University) at the Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies campus. This study focuses on Veeries (Catharus fuscescens), heterospecific eavesdropping, and predation risk. 

The vocalizing Veery for this recording was not seen, as it was passively recorded during a playback experiment (to study the acoustic response of Veeries to the high "seet" alarm call from Tufted Titmice [Baeolophus bicolor]) during the dusk chorus. The recording of this particular Veery call was made during the playback experiment. Since this was a passive playback experiment (i.e. the recorder was not there as to avoid disturbing the avian chorus and an omnidirectional microphone was left to passively record the dusk chorus), plumage features of the vocalizing individual cannot be provided. 

The habitat in which this vocalizing Veery was recorded is a mixed oak forest, largely composed of second-growth oak (Quercus spp.) and maple (Acer spp.). No information is available regarding the bird's position or distance from the microphone. No additional physical behavior is noted; no photographs were taken. This particular recording was not altered or filtered, but it was clipped from a longer (65-minute) recording as part of an experimental playback trial. 
The Veery call in this recording is described as the Chatter call, which is a harsh call characterized by rapid pitch changes, giving the call a rough, “scolding” quality (K. A. Schmidt unpubl. data; Heckscher 2007). Other species heard in this recording include the Eastern Wood Pewee (Contopus virens) and Wood Thrush (Hylocichla mustelina).

This research was supported in part by a grant to K.A. Schmidt from the National Science Foundation (CAREER grant DEB 0746985).

References
Heckscher, C. M. 2007. Use of the Veery (Catharus fuscescens) call repertoire in vocal communication. Thesis. University of Delaware, Newark, Delaware, USA.

recordings.loc: New York (near  Millbrook), Dutchess County, New York
recordings.rmk:
This original record was made by Wieteke A. Holthuijzen as part of a long-term study initiated and supervised by Dr. Kenneth A. Schmidt (Assistant Professor, Behavioral Ecology of Birds and Mammals, Texas Tech University) at the Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies campus. This study focuses on Veeries (Catharus fuscescens), heterospecific eavesdropping, and predation risk. 

The vocalizing Veeries for this recording were not seen, as they were passively recorded during a playback experiment (to study the acoustic response of Veeries to the high "seet" alarm call from Tufted Titmice [Baeolophus bicolor]) during the dusk chorus. The recording of this particular Veery call was made during the playback experiment. Since this was a passive playback experiment (i.e. the recorder was not there as to avoid disturbing the avian chorus and an omnidirectional microphone was left to passively record the dusk chorus), plumage features of the vocalizing individuals cannot be provided. 

The habitat in which this vocalizing Veeries were recorded is a mixed oak forest, largely composed of second-growth oak (Quercus spp.) and maple (Acer spp.). No information is available regarding the birds’ position or distance from the microphone. No additional physical behavior is noted; no photographs were taken. This particular recording was not altered or filtered, but it was clipped from a longer (65-minute) recording as part of an experimental playback trial. 

The Veery call in this recording is described as the “Buerr” call, which is a short call that falls downward at a convex angle, varying between tonal and harsh notes, sometimes with harmonics (K. A. Schmidt unpubl. data; Heckscher 2007 [U call]). Two different vocalizing Veeries are heard in this recording, both vocalizing “Buerr” calls. Two other recordings of different Veery calls were made at this same location within 24 hours (XC362508, XC362509). Another individual Veery can be heard singing in the distant background in this recording as well.

This research was supported in part by a grant to K.A. Schmidt from the National Science Foundation (CAREER grant DEB 0746985).

References
Heckscher, C. M. 2007. Use of the Veery (Catharus fuscescens) call repertoire in vocal communication. Thesis. University of Delaware, Newark, Delaware, USA.

recordings.rmk:
This original record was made by Wieteke A. Holthuijzen as part of a long-term study initiated and supervised by Dr. Kenneth A. Schmidt (Assistant Professor, Behavioral Ecology of Birds and Mammals, Texas Tech University) at the Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies campus. This study focuses on Veeries (Catharus fuscescens), heterospecific eavesdropping, and predation risk. 

The vocalizing Veery for this recording was not seen, as it was passively recorded during a playback experiment (to study the acoustic response of Veeries to the high "seet" alarm call from Tufted Titmice [Baeolophus bicolor]) during the dusk chorus. The recording of this particular Veery call was made during the playback experiment. Since this was a passive playback experiment (i.e. the recorder was not there as to avoid disturbing the avian chorus and an omnidirectional microphone was left to passively record the dusk chorus), plumage features of the vocalizing individual cannot be provided. 

The habitat in which this vocalizing Veery was recorded is a mixed oak forest, largely composed of second-growth oak (Quercus spp.) and maple (Acer spp.). No information is available regarding the bird's position or distance from the microphone. No additional physical behavior is noted; no photographs were taken. This particular recording was not altered or filtered, but it was clipped from a longer (65-minute) recording as part of an experimental playback trial. 

The Veery call in this recording is described as the Tunnel call, which is a relatively short, clear call occurring within a narrow pitch range (2-4 kHz), accompanied by two to three harmonics (K. A. Schmidt unpubl. data). Other species heard in this recording include the Gray Tree Frog (Hyla versicolor). 

This research was supported in part by a grant to K.A. Schmidt from the National Science Foundation (CAREER grant DEB 0746985).

The Veery call in this recording is described as the Whisper call, which is an acoustically complex, low-amplitude call (Belinsky et al. 2015). Another recording of the same type of Veery call was made at this same location within 24 hours (XC362639). In addition, a recording of a different Veery call was recorded within 24 hours at same location (XC362638).

This original record was made by Wieteke A. Holthuijzen as part of a long-term study initiated and supervised by Dr. Kenneth A. Schmidt (Assistant Professor, Behavioral Ecology of Birds and Mammals, Texas Tech University) at the Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies campus. This study focuses on Veeries (Catharus fuscescens), heterospecific eavesdropping, and predation risk. 

The vocalizing Veery for this recording was not seen, as it was passively recorded during a playback experiment (to study the acoustic response of Veeries to the high "seet" alarm call from Tufted Titmice [Baeolophus bicolor]) during the dusk chorus. The recording of this particular Veery call was made before the playback experiment began. Since this was a passive playback experiment (i.e. the recorder was not there as to avoid disturbing the avian chorus and an omnidirectional microphone was left to passively record the dusk chorus), plumage features of the vocalizing individual cannot be provided. 

The habitat in which this vocalizing Veery was recorded is a mixed oak forest, largely composed of second-growth oak (Quercus spp.) and maple (Acer spp.). No information is available regarding the bird's position or distance from the microphone. No additional physical behavior is noted; no photographs were taken. This particular recording was not altered or filtered, but it was clipped from a longer (65-minute) recording as part of an experimental playback trial. This recording was made within a few minutes of another recording (XC362508), so it is likely that this may be the same vocalizing individual. Another recording of a different Veery call was made at this same location within 24 hours (XC362634). 

The Veery call in this recording is described as the “Veer” call, which is a common, short call characterized by a falling pitch (at a generally consistent rate), which may vary in pitch range but remains tonal (WAH pers. obs.; Heckscher 2007 [Downward call]).

This research was supported in part by a grant to K.A. Schmidt from the National Science Foundation (CAREER grant DEB 0746985).

References
Heckscher, C. M. 2007. Use of the Veery (Catharus fuscescens) call repertoire in vocal communication. Thesis. University of Delaware, Newark, Delaware, USA.

recordings.rmk:
# Tug Hill, NY Mystery Bird #
## Warbler? Mockingbird? (strange spiraling, "mechanical" song) ##

The bird I'm trying to identify is the one making what I can only describe as the strange and beautiful _SPIRALING, downward-trilling song_ that starts immediately at _0:00_, then repeats at _0:07_ and _0:18_...

You can hear what I'm guessing is a warbler chirping (short bursts of chirps) in the "foreground" (ie., closer to the recording device) whose call is thus louder than the song I'm trying to identify. I have limited knowledge, but there are many warblers in our area and I have seen "shy," small, yellow birds flitting through the treetops that I suspect are warblers, and based on listening to other files on this site, I have (perhaps incorrectly?) identified the "foreground" (louder, chirping) bird as some sort of warbler, and thus suspected that the Mystery Bird is also a warbler of some kind. However, I've listened to recordings on many sites including this one, and have never heard anything like it - nor have I read what seems to be a description of the song in Audubon...

It seems to me that there may be a call-and-response going on with the Mystery Bird's song being and the chirping of the other bird - this, however, may be an illusion and actually just coincidence...

I have never seen the bird but it seems to come from high up in the tree canopy... 

In the evenings, from about 5:00pm to sunset, the forest is absolutely full of the sound of many Mystery Birds singing this song. In chorus, the song  almost sounds mechanical -- in fact, at first I thought they were some sort of mockingbird that was mimicking a car alarm. However, given the ubiquity of the song and the length of time we've heard this (7+ years now) I no longer think this to be the case...

Whatever the Mystery Bird is, it seems very shy. Not only have I never been able to spot one singing, but they seem to recede from human contact. Eg., sometimes the bird sounds as though it's in our "backyard" but if I go out to record it and make noise such as the screen door slamming closed, the bird will seem to recede into the forest (sound gets fainter)... When walking through the forest in the evening, however, there are so many of these birds that the song is very audible...

The area is rolling hills covered with farmland and successional forest. The immediate area where we hear this bird, however, is densely forested late successional forest of mostly hardwoods (maples, American basswood, beech, and yellow birch) mixed with spruce, fir and hemlocks, surrounding a lake (the Salmon River Reservoir) and streams. The forest floor is also very densely covered with shrubs, ferns, and berries...

I have not modified this recording.

recordings.loc: Upper Walker Creek, Yavapai County, Arizona
recordings.rmk: About 20m away in dense riparian with overstory of primarily large Sycamores and understory of Arizona black walnut, Gambel's oak and grapevine tangles. At first we heard a Catharus thrush song that I wanted to call a Veery but was a bit distant and somewhat drowned out by the stream that I convinced myself it was probably a SWTH since that would be much more likely. As we got closer it continued to sing and we started to become more certain it was actually a Veery. Song of resonant, vaguely metallic trills on a fairly low pitch and descending in pitch as the song progressed. Then it started mixing in typical ‘veer’ calls which are much different than any call a SWTH makes. Unfortunately, I was only able to record the song but the calls were heard quite well and the bird responded with calls to playback of Veery song. Full disclosure, we actually heard the calls before the song and since we're not used to hearing/not expecting a Veery, just thought it was a weird Hooded Oriole call or something, Then it sang and a few of the same calls came from the same place as the song. I played a Veery call from Sibley to jog my memory and it was exactly the call that the bird in question had just uttered. Not a great recording due to stream noise and distance.

Another Veery can be heard singing in the distant background; other species heard in this recording include the Wood Thrush (Hylocichla mustelina) and American Robin (Turdus migratorius). Other recordings of a different Veery call were taken at the same location within 24 hours (XC362639, XC362640).
